06433nam a22007095i 9780822384755DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223847557 a10.1515/97808223847552doi  a(DE-B1597)553464  a(OCoLC)1055304801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLAW0130002bisacsh04a340/.11522100aCultural Analysis, Cultural Studies, and the Law :bMoving Beyond Legal Realism /ced. by Jonathan Simon, Austin D. Sarat. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b4 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tCultural Analysis, Cultural Studies, and the Situation of Legal Scholarship -- tI Approaches to the Cultural Study of Law -- tLaw as Culture -- tWhat It Is and What It Isn’t: Cultural Studies Meets Graduate Student Labor -- tTelling a Less Suspicious Story: Notes toward a Nonskeptical Approach to Legal/Cultural Analysis -- tFreedom, Autonomy, and the Cultural Study of Law -- tII Deploying Law and Legal Ideas in Culture and Society -- tEthnography and Democracy: Texts and Contexts in the United States in the 1990s -- tRules of Law, Laws of Science -- tLaw, Therapy, Culture -- tIII Reading Legal Events -- tA Ghost in the House of Justice: Death and the Language of the Law -- tLacan and Voting Rights -- t‘‘Into the Blue’’: The Image Written on Law -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultural Analysis, Cultural Studies, and the Law is a field-defining collection of work at the intersection of law, cultural analysis and cultural studies. Over the past few decades the marked turn toward claims and policy arguments based on cultural identity—such as ethnicity, race, or religion—has pointed up the urgent need for legal studies to engage cultural critiques. Exploration of legal issues through cultural analyses provides a rich supplement to other approaches—including legal realism, law and economics, and law and society. As Austin Sarat and Jonathan Simon demonstrate, scholars of the law have begun to mine the humanities for new theoretical tools and kinds of knowledge. Crucial to this effort is cultural studies, with its central focus on the relationship between knowledge and power.Drawing on legal scholarship, literary criticism, psychoanalytic theory, and anthropology, the essays collected here exemplify the contributions cultural analysis and cultural studies make to interdisciplinary legal study. Some of these broad-ranging pieces describe particular approaches to the cultural study of the law, while others look at specific moments where the law and culture intersect. Contributors confront the deep connections between law, social science, and post-World War II American liberalism; examine the traffic between legal and late-nineteenth- and early-twentieth-century scientific discourses; and investigate, through a focus on recovered memory, the ways psychotherapy is absorbed into the law. The essayists also explore specific moments where the law is forced to comprehend the world beyond its boundaries, illuminating its dependence on a series of unacknowledged aesthetic, psychological, and cultural assumptions—as in Aldolph Eichmann’s 1957 trial, hiv-related cases, and the U.S. Supreme Court’s recent efforts to define the role of race in the construction of constitutionally adequate voting districts.Contributors. Paul Berman, Peter Brooks, Wai Chee Dimock, Anthony Farley, Shoshanna Felman, Carol Greenhouse, Paul Kahn, Naomi Mezey, Tobey Miller, Austin Sarat, Jonathan Simon, Alison Young  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCulture and law. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bis